<h2>Basic Terms</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Element</strong>: The types of building blocks you use to make a web page, e.g. links</li>
  <li><strong>Tags</strong>: The building blocks in your web page that make it up, a particular link</li>
  <li><strong>Attributes</strong>: Ways to modify the building blocks, e.g. where a link goes to</li>
  <li><strong>Document</strong>: Refers to the whole document that makes up a web page</li>
  <li><strong>Comments</strong>: Pieces of text that are ignored and don't show up (useful for the coder to make notes to other developers)</li>
</ul>

<h2>Elements/Tags/Attributes</h2>
<p>Look at this tag:</p>
<div class="annotated-code">
  <pre class="prettyprint">
&lt;a href='http://www.google.com/'&gt;Go to Google!&lt;/a&gt;</pre>
  <div class="annotation" data-line="1">
    <a href='http://www.google.com/'>Go to Google!</a>
  </div>
</div>

<p>We can say several things about it:</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>&lt;...&gt; <em>contents</em> &lt;/...&gt;</strong> forms the basis of all tags</li>
  <li><strong>a</strong> is the element, which tells what type the tag is (here it means link)</li>
  <li><strong>href</strong> is the attribute that a elements have, which describe where the link should go</li>
  <li>Go to Google! is where the contents of the tag, i.e. the text of the link in this case</li>
</ul>

